Wash and dry produce.

Trim and slice @Scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Dice @Tomato{1} into ½-inch pieces. Trim, peel, and dice @Carrot{3%ounce} into ¼-inch pieces. Trim and quarter @Zucchini{1} lengthwise; cut crosswise into ¼-inch-thick pieces.

Heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{1%teaspoon} in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites, tomato, carrot, @Garlic Powder{1%teaspoon}, @Garam Masala{1%teaspoon}, and @Curry Powder{1%tablespoon}. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, about ~{30-60%seconds}.

Add @Ground Turkey{10%ounce}, a large pinch of @Salt{pinch}, and @Pepper{pinch}; cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until turkey is browned and cooked through, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Meanwhile, finely chop @Cilantro{1/4%ounce}.

In a #small bowl{}, whisk together @Cornstarch{1%tablespoon} and half the @Coconut Milk{1}(all for 4 servings) until dissolved.

Once turkey is done, stir in zucchini, @Veggie Stock Concentrate{2}, half the cilantro, 1¼ cups water, @Sugar{1/2%teaspoon}, and as many @Chili Flakes{1%teaspoon} as you like (2 1/2 cups water and 1 tsp sugar for 4 servings). Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to a low simmer. Cook, stirring occasionally, until zucchini is tender, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Increase heat to high and bring soup to a boil. Slowly drizzle in cornstarch mixture; cook, stirring constantly, until soup has thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Divide soup between #bowls{}; sprinkle with scallion greens and remaining cilantro. Serve.

> Ground Turkey is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.